pr_review_comment_body:
@ghickman I had a comment that disappeared when I pushed a minor fix early yesterday... 

I had a question as to whether it'd be better to put these 404's in the QueryParamsSerializer. I know a non-existent repo or bug id is not technically malformed data, but the downside to putting it here is that if a user has more than one query string param that's incorrect, the serializer will return the field error first (say startday is missing and bug id is non-existent, only the startday error will be returned in the response).  If I move these to the serializer and raise a ValidationError then all errors will return from the serializer. Thoughts? 

ex: localhost:8000/api/failuresbybug/?startday=&endday=2018-02-16&tree=mozilla-inbound&bug=122222222

you could apply the value transformation here, instead of using x.value and so on further down the line. Something like

    for seg in val_iter(isegment(tree_object)):

        seg_diam = seg[0][3] + seg[1][3]

What about
```python
@ABC.register
class ...:
```
?

this does not seem to be correct. it should be sth like:
```scala
if (train) {
  if (!isLazy || !flag(0)) {
     noise.resizeAs(input)
     if (input.isContiguous()) {
       ...
       Engine.model.sync(results)
       this.output
     }
     else {
        ...
        this.output.cmul(noise)
     }
  }
  else {
    output
  }
} else if (!scale) {
  this.output.mul(ev.fromType[Double](1 - p))
} else {
  output
}
```

Here's the definition of `search_units`:

```python
def search_units(cfg, repo, criteria=None, response_handler=None):
    # snip!
    if criteria is None:
        criteria = {}
    if response_handler is None:
        response_handler = api.json_handler
    return api.Client(cfg, response_handler).post(
        urljoin(repo['_href'], 'search/units/'),
        {'criteria': criteria},
    )
```

Notice the default values given to `criteria` and `response_handler`? With that in mind, this line of code can be rewritten as:

```python
units = utils.search_units(cfg, repo)
```
